First, by the median‐length formula, the median from A onto side BC (of length a = 9) is

 \(AM \;=\; m_a \;=\;\tfrac12\sqrt{2b^2+2c^2 - a^2}
                \;=\;\tfrac12\sqrt{2\cdot8^2 + 2\cdot7^2 - 9^2}
                \;=\;\tfrac12\sqrt{145}\,. \)

Next, by Heron’s formula the area of ABC is

 \(s=\tfrac{7+8+9}2=12,\)
 \([ABC]=\sqrt{12\,(12-9)\,(12-8)\,(12-7)}
         =\sqrt{12\cdot3\cdot4\cdot5}
         =12\sqrt5.\)

Hence the desired ratio is

\[
\frac{AM}{[ABC]}
\;=\;\frac{\tfrac12\sqrt{145}}{12\sqrt5}
\;=\;\frac{\sqrt{145}}{24\sqrt5}
\;=\;\frac{\sqrt{29}}{24}
\;\approx\;0.224\quad(\text{to three decimal places}).
\]

First, by the Angle‐Bisector Theorem, if D is on BC with BD∶DC=AB∶AC=6∶7, then  
\[BD=\frac{6}{6+7}\cdot8=\frac{48}{13},\quad DC=\frac{7}{13}\cdot8=\frac{56}{13}.\]  
A standard formula for the length of the bisector from A in a triangle with sides a=BC, b=CA, c=AB is  
\[AD=\sqrt{bc\Bigl[1-\frac{a^2}{(b+c)^2}\Bigr]}\,. \]  
Here a=8, b=7, c=6, so  
\begin{align*}
AD&=\sqrt{7\cdot6\Bigl[1-\frac{8^2}{(7+6)^2}\Bigr]}
=\sqrt{42\Bigl[1-\frac{64}{169}\Bigr]}
=\sqrt{42\cdot\frac{105}{169}}
=\frac{\sqrt{4410}}{13}
=\frac{21\sqrt{10}}{13}\,. 
\end{align*}
Numerically,  
\[AD=\frac{21\sqrt{10}}{13}\approx5.108\,. \]  
Answer (to three decimal places): 5.108
